<TEXT>
<P>
 ALL THE KING'S MEN: Michael and Lisa Marie dueting at the Elvis Presley 
tribute in October? Maybe. The original band that backed Elvis in his early 
days? Maybe not. 
</P>
<P>
 The team putting together the show, scheduled for Oct. 8 at the Pyramid arena 
in Memphis, has been negotiating with guitarist Scotty Moore, drummer D.J. 
Fontana and backup singers the Jordanaires -- the surviving musicians who 
helped shape Presley's sound -- about performing at the show. 
</P>
<P>
 The problem: They want to bring along Ronnie McDowell, an Elvis sound-alike 
country singer they've been working with for the past two years. 
</P>
<P>
 That package has already booked a show the same night in Indiana, but the 
tribute promoters have offered to pay off McDowell in order to free up the rest 
of the group. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm not going to cancel on Ronnie," says Moore, 62. "You just don't do that." 
</P>
<P>
 You can definitely catch the act (McDowell included) on Oct. 16 at the 
Shreveport (La.) Municipal Auditorium, 40 years to the day after the "Louisiana 
Hayride" show that helped spark Elvismania. Steve Hochman 
</P>
